Dijkstra's Algorithm

Dijkstra's algorithm is a single-source shortest path algorithm used to find the shortest weighted distance from a starting node (source) to all other nodes in a graph.

Key Advantages:
It is significantly faster than Bellman-Ford for graphs with non-negative edge weights.
Efficiently finds the shortest path using a min-heap (priority queue).
Note: It fails and gives incorrect results on graphs with negative edge weights.

Complexity:
Time Complexity: O(E * log(V)) (where V is vertices and E is edges, using a priority queue).
Space Complexity: O(V) for the distance array and priority queue.

How it Works (Greedy Approach) // only for revision purpose not detiled steps
Unlike Bellman-Ford (which is Dynamic Programming), Dijkstra uses a Greedy Approach. 
1. We initialize the distance to the source node as 0 and all other nodes to infinity (or a very large number like 1e9).
2. We push the source node and its distance {0, source} into a min-heap (priority queue).
3. We extract the node with the minimum distance from the heap. We then iterate through all its adjacent neighbors. 
4. If the distance to reach the popped node plus the edge weight to the neighbor is less than the current known distance to the neighbor, we update the neighbor's distance.
5. We push the updated {new_distance, neighbor} into the min-heap. We repeat this until the heap is empty.

Q: Why does Dijkstra fail on negative edge weights? //follow up and important comceptual questions with simple and small explanation
Dijkstra assumes that once a node's minimum distance is extracted from the priority queue, it is permanently finalized and cannot be improved. If a negative weight edge exists, it might provide a cheaper path to a previously finalized node later on, breaking the greedy assumption and resulting in incorrect shortest paths.

Implementation (Standard)

vector<int> dijkstra(int V, vector<vector<pair<int, int>>>& adj, int S) {
    // Initialize distances to infinity (1e9), and source to 0
    vector<int> result(V, 1e9);
    result[S] = 0;

    // Min-heap to store {distance, node}
    priority_queue<pair<int, int>, vector<pair<int, int>>, greater<pair<int, int>>> pq;
    pq.push({0, S});

    while(!pq.empty()) {
        int dist = pq.top().first;
        int node = pq.top().second;
        pq.pop();

        // Iterate through all adjacent nodes
        for(auto it : adj[node]) {
            int adjNode = it.first;
            int wt = it.second;

            // If a shorter path is found, update and push to pq
            if(dist + wt < result[adjNode]) {
                result[adjNode] = dist + wt;
                pq.push({result[adjNode], adjNode});
            }
        }
    }

    return result;
}

Implementation (With Path Tracking) // other imp variations of this algo or topic

If we also need to reconstruct the actual shortest path from the source to any node, we can maintain a parent array. Every time we successfully find a shorter path to an adjacent node, we update its parent.

vector<int> dijkstra_with_path(int V, vector<vector<pair<int, int>>>& adj, int S, vector<int>& parent) {
    vector<int> result(V, 1e9);
    
    // Resize and initialize parent array to -1
    parent.assign(V, -1); 
    result[S] = 0;

    priority_queue<pair<int, int>, vector<pair<int, int>>, greater<pair<int, int>>> pq;
    pq.push({0, S});

    while(!pq.empty()) {
        int dist = pq.top().first;
        int node = pq.top().second;
        pq.pop();

        for(auto it : adj[node]) {
            int adjNode = it.first;
            int wt = it.second;

            if(dist + wt < result[adjNode]) {
                result[adjNode] = dist + wt;
                parent[adjNode] = node; // Track the node we came from
                pq.push({result[adjNode], adjNode});
            }
        }
    }

    return result;
}
